Gdistance(2G)        GRASS Reference Manual         Gdistance(2G)



RULES
     After entering the Gdistance command line (if the user is
     not directing a UNIX rules file into Gdistance), a (>)
     prompt will appear. At the prompt, the user enters:

     (1) the selected categories in the existing data layer from
     which distances shall be calculated. In the example below,
     distances are calculated for categories 2, 6, 7, 8, 10 and
     14.

          FORMAT:
          > cats# # # [etc.]

          EXAMPLE:
          > cats 2 6 7 8
          > cats 10 14

     (2) the distance zones desired. The user has the option of
     identifying up to 60 continuous zones. The zones are
     identified by specifying the upper limit of each desired
     zone (Gdistance assumes that 0 is the starting point). In
     the example below, the distance zones would be (in cells):
     010, 1120, 2130, 3140 and 4150.

          Format:
          > dist # # # [etc.]

          Example:
          > dist 10 20 30
          > dist 40 50

     (3) end   (This tells Gdistance to terminate input and start
     creating the new cell file.)

          Format:
          > end

NOTES
     Gdistance only works on square cells in the current window.
     Gdistance will complain if cells are not square.

SEE ALSO
     distance[1]

AUTHOR
     Dave Gerdes, U.S. Army Construction Engineering Research
     Laboratory.








